                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d572">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12562: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-12T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 12, 1933—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 12—3:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>906. Reference Department’s 389, December 6. Following telegram has been received
                    from the Minister.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“December 11, 11 a.m. I propose to inform Foreign Office orally of
                        Department’s views. British method of meeting situation by permitting search
                        in presence of British naval officers seems to me to be a common-sense
                        method. I wonder whether Department would agree to this method in view of
                        British action and in view of physical difficulties attending arrangement
                        for customs search.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
